This week, we=E2=80=99re envying foxes, seeking a Midnight Friend, justifyi=
ng our Carhartts, and listening to ghosts.
FABLES
Comfort or freedom
Katy Kelleher considers the contrasting lessons of a classic fable, and how=
 they each resonate in a current context of economic precarity.
I=E2=80=99d like to be more wild. [ https://substack.com/redirect/f353c0a7-=
c03c-4496-9cec-f90815e8c417?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwd=
Yu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Katy Kelleher  in Eat Flowers, Drink Paint =20
I=E2=80=99ve heard the story told several different ways, but the bones of =
it are always the same. A well-fed dog is lying outside a house, tied up on=
 his leash, minding his own business. A fox (or sometimes a coyote, sometim=
es a wolf) pokes his head out of the nearby forest and begins to lope over.=
 The dog raises his hackles, the fox bares his teeth. But soon enough, the =
two canines begin to talk. The subject matter? Oh, just their lives. How th=
ey spend their days, how they sleep at night.
At first, the fox is awed by the creature comforts enjoyed by the dog. Ther=
e=E2=80=99s easily digested bowls of kibble, delivered at regular intervals=
, for which he only needs to pant and wait. There=E2=80=99s the occasional =
foray onto the furniture, soft and plush below his bulging belly. Warmth ra=
diates from the hearth or the heater. Life sounds easy; that sounds good.
But then, there=E2=80=99s the turn, the trick, the twist revealed. =E2=80=
=9CWhen do you run free across the field, shouting at the sky?=E2=80=9D ask=
s the fox. =E2=80=9COnly when I=E2=80=99m allowed,=E2=80=9D says the dog. =
=E2=80=9CWhen do you tear your teeth into a rodent=E2=80=99s back and feel =
their small bones break in your jaws and savor that savage joy?=E2=80=9D as=
ks the fox. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know what you=E2=80=99re talking about=
,=E2=80=9D says the dog. =E2=80=9CFood is soft and plentiful. I don=E2=80=
=99t have to hunt for it.=E2=80=9D The two part ways, each thinking the oth=
er a little odd. The dog remains content, if baffled by the visit. (Though =
perhaps a stab of envy will plague him later, when he sees the moon from th=
e window and hears the fox yowling from the woods.) The fox prowls off, car=
rying his own burden of envy a short ways before setting it down, hopefully=
 for good.
I lied earlier. The story isn=E2=80=99t always the same, because the lesson=
 can be quite different. In Aesop=E2=80=99s version, the fox is a wolf, and=
 the moral comes down clearly on the side of the wild canine. =E2=80=9CTher=
e is nothing worth so much as liberty,=E2=80=9D reads one version. =E2=80=
=9CBetter starve free than be a fat slave=E2=80=9D is another. But not ever=
yone identifies with the wolf. According to Wikipedia, an 1818 telling conc=
ludes that =E2=80=9Cliberty in a state of society does not consist in doing=
 whatsoever we please=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca certain portion of individual=
 liberty must be given up for the good of the whole.=E2=80=9D Team dog, the=
n, I guess.
The version I chose, and the one I heard most recently, came from a childre=
n=E2=80=99s storytelling podcast. (On good days, when we=E2=80=99re both in=
 high spirits and focused moods, I like to play stories for Juniper while s=
he crafts and I cook. She=E2=80=99s six and I worry that these days are num=
bered, so for now I try to savor them fiercely.) The tale ends with a simpl=
e, inclusive message, implying that neither the fox nor the dog was in the =
right. =E2=80=9CTo each their own,=E2=80=9D says the narrator generously.
That bit about envy? I admit, I added that. Because that=E2=80=99s how I re=
ad it. We=E2=80=99re all living in our own very particular homes, construct=
ed from a million branches of choice, twigs stacked willy-nilly around us, =
seemingly stable nests made of too many forking paths. Our lives are precar=
ious and precious, built through years of wanting, waiting, choosing, chang=
ing, trying, failing, flying, failing. Part of it boils down to our identit=
ies (are you a dog or a wolf?), but our fates are also determined by whethe=
r we choose wilderness or stability, individualism or conformity, selfishne=
ss or community.
