MUSIC
Chasing ghosts
Jason Diamond on Lou Reed=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CHalloween Parade,=E2=80=9D a s=
ong that manages to mourn the dead while being neither solemn nor spooky.
Lou Reed=E2=80=99s Beautiful Halloween Dirge [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/35f7d6e6-4b44-4f1f-9270-7eac979f8310?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCo=
upjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Jason Diamond  in The Melt by Jason Diamond  =20
=E2=80=9CHalloween Parade=E2=80=9D isn=E2=80=99t a ghost song; Reed wrote a=
 song that=E2=80=99s about searching for ghosts. Written at the height of t=
he AIDS crisis, he mentions a number of characters with names like Harry, V=
irgin Mary, Rotten Rita, and Johnny Rio who used to go to the parade, but =
=E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99ll never see those faces again.=E2=80=9D Musically, it=
 doesn=E2=80=99t sound especially sad, but it=E2=80=99s not one you=E2=80=
=99re going to put on a Halloween party playlist between =E2=80=9CThe Monst=
er Mash=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CDracula=E2=80=99s Wedding=E2=80=9D by Outkast=
=2E =E2=80=9CHalloween Parade=E2=80=9D won=
=E2=80=99t get the party bumping.
But putting it on is a way to introduce yourself to Reed=E2=80=99s most end=
uring solo work. Transformer is his most well-known and Metal Machine Music=
 will always be one of those records people will swear up and down is a min=
imalist masterpiece and if you don=E2=80=99t get that then you don=E2=80=99=
t understand music, but New York is his most American. The name might make =
you think otherwise, but when I put it on for the first time this season, t=
he first lyrics on the opening track, =E2=80=9CRomeo Had Juliette,=E2=80=9D=
 grabbed me:
Caught between the twisted stars
The plotted lines the faulty map
That brought Columbus to New York
It=E2=80=99s about New York City characters that consumed Reed, but it all =
starts with America=E2=80=99s original sin of being discovered by Christoph=
er Columbus. All the down-and-out, broken angels he writes about on the alb=
um, the poor or drug-addicted folks, the people who died from a disease the=
 government neglected, and that overwhelming sadness you can=E2=80=99t esca=
pe, all of it feels a lot like 2025 to me. But when I finish listening to t=
he album, I=E2=80=99ll usually play =E2=80=9CHalloween Parade=E2=80=9D once=
 or twice more, and I always appreciate it how Reed offers this tiny glimps=
e of hopefulness by ending the track by saying, =E2=80=9CSee you next year,=
 at the Halloween parade.=E2=80=9D He spends the whole song singing about t=
he people he misses, but he brings it home by reminding us there=E2=80=99s =
always tomorrow. And sure, you=E2=80=99ll still be sad and missing people y=
ou loved when you wake up, but that=E2=80=99s life in the big city. Take th=
e bad with the good and just keep going.
